WEBVTT

00:02.914 --> 00:08.679
We said it's like Russian roulette with these chairs, because last time I interviewed Dave on one of these chairs, it just suddenly collapsed on him.

00:08.699 --> 00:12.583
So we've had a little conversation about where the health and safety permit.

00:13.304 --> 00:15.346
Also, you're a lot higher than I am, but that's all good.

00:15.366 --> 00:16.327
I'll just look up to you.

00:17.988 --> 00:18.649
Do you feel safe?

00:18.669 --> 00:19.750
I feel really safe.

00:19.830 --> 00:23.153
I can't put my...

00:24.975 --> 00:25.936
I need an assistant.

00:27.117 --> 00:31.081
And also, it keeps on randomly drifting this way, so...

00:31.101 --> 00:32.562
It's a bit distracting, isn't it?

00:32.866 --> 00:33.347
I'm ready.

00:33.367 --> 00:33.807
It's OK.

00:33.907 --> 00:34.428
It's OK.

00:34.588 --> 00:35.329
Try not to move.

00:38.373 --> 00:38.873
Morning, Dave.

00:39.014 --> 00:39.855
Good morning, friend.

00:39.875 --> 00:41.396
It's good to have you with us again.

00:41.436 --> 00:53.832
I just want to frame what we're about to launch into because, as pretty much everybody in this room, but a few may not know, we are heading into our Centenary year here as a church.

00:54.312 --> 01:02.322
And Skylark Church began with a lady called Rose Wibrow, who saw a group of kids playing outside

01:02.690 --> 01:28.722
her window and her heart was moved with compassion and she just knew she needed to do something and so she opened her home back in 1926 and invited them in and began a Sunday school in her home and from that our church began and we have been thinking since the start of this year what legacy could we leave for generations to come if we

01:28.802 --> 01:35.651
collectively and individually stepped into the story that God is continuing to write in and through this church.

01:35.691 --> 01:38.835
And I think our beginnings are really important.

01:39.736 --> 01:50.169
So as part of that series, when I heard the subject of your latest book, which has not yet been released, release date is when?

01:50.409 --> 01:51.230
April the 20th.

01:51.390 --> 01:55.616
And you guys are the very first people in the entire world to hear about here.

01:56.176 --> 01:57.458
Come on!

01:57.666 --> 02:02.456
Yes, you heard it here first, Skylark Church, that's pioneering and it's finest.

02:02.556 --> 02:03.738
Let's hope you're not the last day.

02:05.442 --> 02:06.003
Definitely.

02:06.043 --> 02:11.634
Raising Generation Alpha is the title of your book and

02:11.746 --> 02:28.152
I think that certainly in church circles lately, we have heard so much about Generation Z and about the quiet revival and how there's a whole heap of young adults kind of really encountering Jesus and hungry for a spiritual journey.

02:28.613 --> 02:32.679
But nobody really is talking about Generation Alpha, are they?

02:32.899 --> 02:39.570
They're not, and believe it or not, and I've had this conversation with John this morning, Generation Alpha is technically already finished.

02:39.746 --> 02:48.658
Yeah, because we're already into Generation Beta at the start of 2025, and yet the church is not talking about this generation, which is really the heart behind the book.

02:49.099 --> 02:51.843
Come on, and that's such a good heart behind the book.

02:52.544 --> 02:55.748
There's so much that resonated with me as I read the book.

02:55.768 --> 03:04.600
I parents to children who fall into Generation Alpha, so I felt encouraged and challenged in equal measure.

03:04.740 --> 03:08.786
I think I've highlighted about 75% of what I read.

03:08.866 --> 03:13.593
And I don't know that we'll be able to cover all of the questions that I have for you today.

03:13.633 --> 03:30.299
But what my heart would be that as we sit here today, whether we have any relationship to someone in Gen Alpha or whether we feel fairly removed from that, we would understand that this is an important part of the legacy that we can write into the future.

03:30.339 --> 03:32.042
Yeah, it's huge.

03:32.062 --> 03:33.023
It's the heart of God, isn't it?

03:33.504 --> 03:34.586
Come on, exactly.

03:34.606 --> 03:36.128
So let's dive in, shall we?

03:37.410 --> 03:37.490
Yes.

03:38.466 --> 03:47.615
The opening few paragraphs of your book has this beautiful little phrase, generation alpha needs you and you need them too.

03:47.775 --> 03:50.698
And that kind of sums up the core message of the book for you.

03:51.098 --> 04:04.291
So can you just begin by framing the essence of the book and why it should matter to us as the church with the capital C to have a better understanding of generations in general and then particularly gen alpha?

04:04.411 --> 04:07.954
Yes, so if you think about it, the heart of God

04:08.034 --> 04:09.356
is multi-generational.

04:10.097 --> 04:20.069
So when God introduced himself to Moses, Moses did not have a clue who God was until he said, I am the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.

04:20.710 --> 04:23.493
So we serve a multi-generational God, don't we?

04:23.994 --> 04:24.314
Absolutely.

04:24.334 --> 04:28.380
And then we think about what is the heart of God for us as the church?

04:28.980 --> 04:31.604
Well, God clearly commands us throughout Scripture.

04:31.624 --> 04:36.690
When you begin to read about generations, you find it everywhere, all from the Old Testament to the New.

04:36.834 --> 04:43.222
And God tells you and me that one generation will tell the story of God to the next.

04:44.143 --> 04:53.174
So there's something about the storification, which is a word I've never used before, of the next generation, that is happening wherever not we like it or not.

04:53.194 --> 04:57.960
So we have to make a decision as the church whose story is going to be told to generation alpha.

04:58.701 --> 05:02.206
And we have to believe that it is the story of God, not the story of culture.

05:03.067 --> 05:05.810
And I guess furthermore that if you wanted to

05:05.954 --> 05:08.637
really mess up with the kingdom of God.

05:08.677 --> 05:28.958
One of the greatest things that you would do is sorry to kind of teach you a hack of how to beat this all up here is that you would actually try to disrupt generations and you would get them speaking against each other and you would try to disconnect them because if you can disconnect generations then you disrupt in the story of God being told to the next generation.

05:30.540 --> 05:32.402
So therefore we as the church

05:32.514 --> 05:36.238
we have to be actively engaged in what God is doing in the next generation.

05:37.078 --> 05:41.563
And I think there's been so much fear when we think about the next generation.

05:42.243 --> 05:43.705
Let's be honest, abdication.

05:44.205 --> 05:57.538
Let's be honest, if we're not talking about generation alpha and it's finished, maybe we need to kind of hold our hand up and say, maybe there's something in this for us of saying, God, how can we best serve this next generation?

05:58.139 --> 06:01.362
And ultimately we have a Jesus who was incredibly

06:01.506 --> 06:04.650
passionate about children, incredibly passionate.

06:04.991 --> 06:08.816
And in fact, when he cleared the temple, what happened?

06:09.337 --> 06:10.639
He got rid of all the rubbish.

06:10.679 --> 06:11.900
He got rid of all the religion.

06:12.461 --> 06:17.288
And he allowed the children to confront and censor of the house of God.

06:17.989 --> 06:21.834
And when he allowed the children to confront and censor the house of God, they began to sing.

06:22.355 --> 06:26.861
And Jesus said, out of the mouths of children, you have ordained praise.

06:27.442 --> 06:30.706
And if you go back into the Old Testament where Jesus is quoting from,

06:30.818 --> 06:34.103
That scripture is a warfare-based scripture.

06:34.904 --> 06:43.096
It's actually in the context of when you're going to war, you have to put the children out front, and the children's voices need to be heard first, and that is an act of war.

06:43.577 --> 06:53.031
So if we want to move forward in advance to the kingdom of God, we have to put children front and centre, and we have to allow them to be who God's called them to be, and that's how we extend the kingdom of God.

06:53.692 --> 06:54.493
I mean, wow.

06:55.274 --> 06:55.935
Mind blown.

06:56.636 --> 06:58.098
Love that.

06:58.338 --> 07:08.819
Just for the benefit of those who have not yet read your book or even researched Generation Alpha, can you just explain who Generation Alpha are in terms of years?

07:08.879 --> 07:18.578
And then just a little snapshot of your acronym, which is actually sort of the key behind the book, A-L-P-H-A.

07:19.554 --> 07:22.457
So Generation Alpha children born from 2010 to 2024.

07:23.118 --> 07:31.347
It's probably worth giving a huge caveat that whenever you look about generational thinking, it is this crossover.

07:31.728 --> 07:38.776
Even as I put this out on Facebook this week, people are going, well, I believe that Generation Alpha talks in 2011, that's fine.

07:38.916 --> 07:40.077
It doesn't really matter.

07:40.638 --> 07:44.242
The whole point, what's interesting is it's generational research

07:44.354 --> 07:46.757
that comes from the Crindall Research in Australia.

07:47.238 --> 07:51.864
And the reason they named Generation Alpha was they got to the end of the alphabet, remember?

07:51.884 --> 07:56.229
So we had Generation X, Generation Y, or Millennials, Generation Z.

07:56.490 --> 07:58.793
And then they were like, do we just start again with A?

07:59.373 --> 08:03.959
And they came to the conclusion by looking at culture that we weren't just in a different chapter.

08:04.400 --> 08:06.302
We were in a different library altogether.

08:06.483 --> 08:08.585
So we have to change the very language.

08:09.206 --> 08:12.210
So that's why they moved the alphabet and became Generation Alpha.

08:12.866 --> 08:15.346
I mean, that in itself is phenomenal, isn't it?

08:15.366 --> 08:18.290
It's why we need to talk about them.

08:18.498 --> 08:24.303
I did about two years' worth of research, and obviously a lot of my background is working with children and young people.

08:24.603 --> 08:30.108
I also have a generation alpha kid myself, and she's in charge of my household.

08:30.468 --> 08:30.909
Wonderful.

08:31.509 --> 08:32.090
What a blessing.

08:32.450 --> 08:38.515
And basically came up with this acronym to try to communicate what's going on for this generation.

08:38.936 --> 08:42.739
And maybe some of the gen alphas in the room will be able to affirm or deny this later.

08:43.099 --> 08:45.441
So it's great to have you guys in the room today.

08:45.862 --> 08:48.484
And effectively, this generation are, A, anxious

08:48.464 --> 09:02.883
B, leading influencers, P, pandemic impacted, H, hyper-connected, and A, AI-shaped.

09:04.686 --> 09:07.950
And that really forms the whole basis of the book.

09:07.970 --> 09:16.722
So we've got the most anxious-minded generation in the whole of history, one in four meet the criteria for an identifiable mental challenge or illness.

09:17.026 --> 09:24.795
We've got leading influences where two-thirds of them want to buy from businesses that will make a huge difference in the world and they want to be actively involved.

09:25.355 --> 09:38.010
We've got pandemic impacted where 84% of parents believe that COVID and Generation C, as they're often called, will have a huge impact on the future of Generation Alpha as it has in all of us.

09:38.630 --> 09:41.874
We've got hyper-connected, so we've got 100% of

09:42.050 --> 09:52.389
generation alpha will lead 100% digital world and this is the way the world has gone and it's going and then we've got AI shapes where 65% of generation alpha kids will work in jobs that do not yet exist.

09:54.172 --> 09:57.458
Okay so that's it's fascinating isn't it to hear that and

09:57.730 --> 10:06.065
Dave, you write, when we understand the world that shapes each generation, we can disciple them with greater intention.

10:06.085 --> 10:20.050
And I love that, because actually, the more that I read about those five traits that you have earmarked for that generation, and I realize it's probably not an exhaustive list, but those are the five kind of headlines.

10:20.162 --> 10:33.467
It helped me think, oh, this is helpful to even know how I can disciple my own kids better, let alone lead a church that is geared towards and empowering that generation to take their place.

10:34.088 --> 10:43.346
Now, I want to move as much as I can into those five areas and my hope is that we have time to cover them all because I feel like we'll miss out if we

10:43.618 --> 11:05.202
if we don't but starting then some of the stats in your book are they're pretty staggering and when it comes to the first defining feature anxious-minded it makes pretty sobering reading to be honest and I realise that we've got some of our youth in the room today and we're going to offer you hope

11:05.410 --> 11:06.471
in this conversation.

11:06.532 --> 11:11.338
The purpose of us sharing some of these stats and not to make anybody feel afraid.

11:11.939 --> 11:15.224
It may be triggering in places, but we're here to support you in that.

11:15.644 --> 11:22.113
But it's important that we understand the reality that we're walking into so that we can also find the hope.

11:22.153 --> 11:26.479
And there's so much hope that comes out of your book and so much hope for this generation.

11:27.040 --> 11:34.130
So one of the quotes that I picked up about this, you said, today's young people

11:34.626 --> 11:38.473
are the most anxious minded in all history.

11:39.594 --> 11:41.257
Can we unpack this some more together?

11:41.277 --> 11:50.193
What signs can we look out for when it comes to anxiety in gen alpha kids, particularly when it comes to thinking, language and behavior?

11:50.213 --> 11:55.762
And what are some of the contributing factors behind this epidemic of anxiety?

11:56.290 --> 11:58.132
So it is so ring, isn't it?

11:58.152 --> 12:09.866
And it's important to recognise we're not talking as therapists today and we're talking about generalised anxiety and also recognising that there's a huge amount of diversity in terms of backgrounds and neurodiverse in the room.

12:09.886 --> 12:16.273
So when we talk to, let's just, we're going to talk generally from what the stats are saying and what the culture is reflecting.

12:17.314 --> 12:23.922
So I believe that we are expecting children to deal with adult sized problems

12:24.674 --> 12:28.220
with in childlike brains using childlike tools.

12:29.442 --> 12:29.943
Simple as that.

12:30.524 --> 12:35.313
So we are, there has been a cultural mission to eradicate childhood.

12:36.174 --> 12:37.677
Right, I would concur with that.

12:38.218 --> 12:47.634
So that's the context that we're talking in and you can see me get angry now because that is the context and it is a work of evil to try to eradicate childhood.

12:48.002 --> 12:52.088
because how can we serve children when we say that children don't exist in the first place?

12:52.108 --> 12:56.054
So people think that if you can blur the boundaries so much that everybody's an adult and we're all okay.

12:56.074 --> 13:04.806
So because those boundaries have been blurred, what happens is, one of the phrases which I don't use in the book, which I wish I had, is anxiety is like an onion.

13:05.427 --> 13:07.690
It has lots of layers and sometimes it makes you cry.

13:09.613 --> 13:14.120
And if you think about the layers that young people are facing today, they are plentiful.

13:14.220 --> 13:15.762
There is more pressure

13:16.162 --> 13:19.305
on the academic achievement in school than ever before.

13:20.126 --> 13:23.129
And schools are not the same places that you and I grew up in.

13:23.610 --> 13:28.194
I work with schools, and I know that they are incredibly challenging places to learn.

13:29.195 --> 13:32.018
Often for young people, school is about survival, not learning.

13:32.479 --> 13:33.720
That's the context of learning it.

13:33.740 --> 13:43.250
And what's happened is, because schools offer a one-size-fits-all criteria, and then say that if you don't fit the something wrong with you, rather than something wrong with the system,

13:44.098 --> 13:44.498
Hello.

13:45.239 --> 13:50.985
What we have is young people are a tremendous amount of pressure when it comes to academic performance.

13:51.005 --> 13:53.508
Secondly, relationships are harder than ever before.

13:53.988 --> 14:02.317
Actually, having friendships, we've lost the skills to have great relationships and great friendships that are becoming more fractured, more broken than ever.

14:02.757 --> 14:05.780
And the online world has made that worse, not better.

14:06.301 --> 14:11.186
So often when I'm talking with my daughter and she's saying, Dad, I said this to my person or I'm having this

14:11.426 --> 14:14.510
upset or arguing with his friend and I'm like, so what did they say to you?

14:14.530 --> 14:15.872
I said, oh no, they didn't say anything.

14:15.912 --> 14:16.673
They watched that me.

14:19.077 --> 14:24.684
So for this generation, the digital and online offline ones, they're interchangeable.

14:25.125 --> 14:26.807
There's no distinction between the two.

14:27.288 --> 14:30.593
So we have to recognise that causes a degree of anxiety and pressure.

14:30.833 --> 14:32.335
And there's no switch off, is there?

14:32.355 --> 14:33.236
There's no switch off.

14:33.256 --> 14:34.578
You never get away from it.

14:34.882 --> 14:42.695
So, you know, you have all these compounding issues, whether it be social comparison, social media, screens.

14:43.416 --> 14:48.845
You know, the kind of like the world that we live in is becoming scary and scary.

14:48.925 --> 14:51.509
Let's be honest, for an adult, it is challenging.

14:51.950 --> 15:01.586
And young people have been early exposed to all these things, and we're not helping equip them with the tools to be able to deal with it, because we're not talking about it.

15:01.922 --> 15:05.355
So that's the context here that we're living in.

15:06.097 --> 15:10.674
And I think, in one sense, it's the same with all generations, isn't it?

15:11.010 --> 15:15.294
And we can talk about how we begin to tackle it if you want briefly.

15:15.734 --> 15:27.105
But I think one of the things that I really feel very strongly about, because it's quite a negative label to say anxious minded, but it's so important to recognize that this is the culture and the sea that young people are swimming in today.

15:27.606 --> 15:30.208
So you might as well tackle it first, if that makes sense.

15:30.228 --> 15:32.290
Definitely, it's just pulling the plaster off, isn't it?

15:32.750 --> 15:36.454
And naming the reality that they face day in, day out.

15:37.195 --> 15:40.818
It would be nice to know, firstly, I suppose, how

15:40.962 --> 15:45.109
do we pick up on that in terms of behaviour, language, thinking?

15:45.149 --> 15:53.842
But also, what kind of tools can you equip us with to help lead young people towards a place of peace?

15:54.664 --> 16:03.698
OK, so I think what we want to be doing is looking for when a young person's world begins to shrink to the point where problems become bigger.

16:04.290 --> 16:07.534
and I think all of us face anxiety different times.

16:07.574 --> 16:18.947
Anxiety, if you think about fear, fears like a match, so you light the match and fear occurs in rightly, so it's actually, you know, if you're walking by the side of a cliff, you need to feel fear of a wise, you'll fall off it, right?

16:19.568 --> 16:25.995
So the match is supposed to get lit and then it burns out when you move away from the side of the cliff, job done.

16:26.756 --> 16:31.602
Anxiety is like a bunch of matches that have been thrown into your heart

16:31.714 --> 16:38.645
One of them has been triggered off, now all of them are going and we can no longer identify where the origin of that thing came from and it just doesn't stop.

16:39.006 --> 16:39.807
That's anxiety.

16:40.108 --> 16:41.290
That's such a helpful analogy.

16:41.310 --> 16:51.186
So I think for us as parents, as those educating, raising the next generation, we want to be looking for when does this become overwhelming and whether there's

16:51.266 --> 16:58.156
Avoidance behaviors happening whether this kind of behaviors where they begin to act a little bit odd Why why is this rather than?

16:58.837 --> 17:13.938
We've mentioned this at the sky laughing rather than mean furious about it become curious about it So one of the first things we can do is enter the world of a young person Put ourself in their shoes and I begin to ask good questions about what's really going on rather than just judging the behavior and

17:14.274 --> 17:16.437
Because you might be thinking that Paul would behave.

17:16.457 --> 17:17.378
And this happens in schools.

17:17.718 --> 17:22.223
All the time, as we know, Emma, is that we call it Paul behavior, but really it's just a coping mechanism.

17:22.824 --> 17:25.707
So we want to be a bit more curious about what's going on and look for it.

17:26.128 --> 17:28.771
And there's a tool that I can teach us in one minute.

17:28.791 --> 17:29.291
Yes, please.

17:29.311 --> 17:35.078
And I decided that I'm going to use a real life kind of vulnerable example of this, OK?

17:35.679 --> 17:35.799
Great.

17:35.819 --> 17:41.906
So last night, I was sat at the dinner table, and I began to feel very, very anxious about today.

17:42.626 --> 17:47.073
And I'm not normally somebody that gets nervous, but I began to feel really, really nervous about today.

17:47.093 --> 17:49.698
And I actually shared it with my family.

17:49.718 --> 17:51.080
I said, guys, can you pray for me?

17:51.120 --> 17:54.366
Because I just feel really nervous about tomorrow.

17:54.706 --> 17:55.307
I didn't know why.

17:55.347 --> 17:58.252
So then I went for a walk, as some times do.

17:58.873 --> 18:00.957
And the Holy Spirit dropped into my heart.

18:00.997 --> 18:04.242
You need to apply the model from your book.

18:04.834 --> 18:05.835
Thanks, Lord.

18:07.557 --> 18:09.319
My relationship with Jesus is interesting as ever.

18:09.860 --> 18:15.947
And there's a little model that we use in the book called The Sea, which stands for situation, emotion, evaluate.

18:16.067 --> 18:16.608
Really simple.

18:17.388 --> 18:21.073
And in essence, it's based on this idea that you examine the situation.

18:21.113 --> 18:26.699
So for me, the situation was, I'm coming to Skylark to speak in front of lots of people.

18:26.719 --> 18:30.464
I do not have notes in front of me, and it's the first time I've talked about this book.

18:31.725 --> 18:32.626
That's Matthew.

18:32.770 --> 18:34.833
Emotion, I feel anxious.

18:35.473 --> 18:43.203
The anxieties manifesting in my shoulders, I feel tight in my stomach and my hands are starting to shake and I'm distracted from everything else.

18:44.064 --> 18:44.685
Evaluate.

18:45.766 --> 18:47.208
And this is where it gets really interesting.

18:47.228 --> 18:50.972
So on my walk, I began to evaluate why was I feeling anxious?

18:51.613 --> 18:54.537
And it's because I was believing some things.

18:55.378 --> 18:58.802
I was believing that I wasn't enough to be able to share this topic.

18:59.298 --> 19:00.660
I'm not an expert in it.

19:00.720 --> 19:01.882
I'm not a psychologist.

19:01.942 --> 19:03.364
I'm not a kind of researcher.

19:03.905 --> 19:10.514
I began to, I believe that people would just think, oh, Dave's out to sell another book again, which by the way, I have a day job.

19:10.554 --> 19:11.316
So thank you very much.

19:11.856 --> 19:12.818
I'm not doing this for many.

19:13.619 --> 19:16.623
And I began to believe all these negative things that I was not enough.

19:17.605 --> 19:22.131
Second part of evaluation is you replace that negativity with the truth of the word of God.

19:23.093 --> 19:23.974
And this is what happened.

19:24.335 --> 19:26.738
I reminded myself of three very simple things.

19:27.234 --> 19:29.337
Number one, God told me to write this book.

19:31.020 --> 19:33.403
Number two, I really believe this book will help people.

19:34.084 --> 19:36.007
And number three, and you'll like this one, church.

19:36.448 --> 19:37.890
Skylark are my family.

19:39.112 --> 19:43.458
Yay!

19:43.478 --> 19:48.486
No word of a lie within 10 seconds, 90% of my anxiety had gone.

19:49.327 --> 19:49.648
Wow.

19:50.509 --> 19:52.852
Because I replaced fear with the truth.

19:53.674 --> 19:56.658
And what happens when we have truth, the truth does what?

19:56.898 --> 19:57.759
That's us three.

19:58.260 --> 20:01.325
So that is one way we can really help our children process.

20:01.906 --> 20:02.707
That is great.

20:02.867 --> 20:04.550
S-E-A-C. S-E-A-C.

20:04.871 --> 20:06.493
It's just literally situation.

20:06.854 --> 20:07.995
What's going on?

20:08.316 --> 20:09.157
What are you feeling?

20:09.918 --> 20:13.624
And remember, it's not what happens to us that makes us anxious.

20:14.185 --> 20:17.470
It's what we believe about what happens to us that makes us anxious.

20:17.911 --> 20:19.794
You change the belief, you change the feeling.

20:20.098 --> 20:22.240
And that's vital, isn't it, actually?

20:22.260 --> 20:25.865
